Feature Engineering

We begin by engineering an number of features.

  1. Create a total of 10 features (including points).
  2. Remove all rows with a missing value.
  3. Ensure only log(price) and engineering features are the only columns that remain in the wino dataframe.
wino <- wine %>% 
  mutate(fr = (country == "France")) %>% #1
  mutate(cab = str_detect(variety, "Cabernet")) %>% #2
  mutate(lprice = log(price)) %>% #3
  mutate(lpoints = log(points))%>% #4
  mutate(wine_age = 2025 - year)%>% #5
  mutate(wine_country = as.factor(country))%>% #6
  mutate(wine_variety = as.factor(variety))%>% #7
  mutate(region_interaction = paste(region_1, region_2, sep = "_"))%>% #8
#  mutate(price_per_point = price / points)%>% #9
  mutate(points_scaled = (points - min(points)) / (max(points) - min(points)))%>%
  mutate(taster_reviews_count = as.numeric(table(taster_name)[taster_name]))%>%
  drop_na(fr, cab) %>%
  select(lprice, points, fr, cab, lpoints, wine_age, wine_country, wine_variety, points_scaled, taster_reviews_count)

Caret

We now use a train/test split to evaluate the features.

  1. Use the Caret library to partition the wino dataframe into an 80/20 split.
wine_index <- createDataPartition(wino$lprice, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
wino_tr <- wino[wine_index, ]
wino_te <- wino[-wine_index, ]
  1. Run a linear regression with bootstrap resampling.
m1 <- train(lprice ~ .,
  data = wino_tr,
  method = "lm",
  trControl = trainControl(method = "boot", number = 5, repeats = 3)
)

  1. Report RMSE on the test partition of the data.
predictions <- predict(m1, newdata = wino_te)
rmse <- sqrt(mean((predictions - wino_te$lprice)^2))
print(paste("RMSE on the test partition:", round(rmse, 4)))

Variable selection

We now graph the importance of your 10 features.

plot(varImp(m1, scale = TRUE)) 
importance <- varImp(m1, scale = FALSE)


importance_df <- data.frame(Predictor = rownames(importance$importance),
                            Importance = importance$importance$Overall)

importance_df%>%
  top_n(10)%>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Predictor, y=Importance))+
  geom_point()+
  theme_bw()+
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1))
